\c 3
\p
\v 1 Hence, holy brothers, who share in a heavenly calling, think about Jesus, the apostle and high priest of our confession,
\v 2 who was faithful to the one who appointed him,\f + Greek ποιήσαντι. BDAG, ESV, NET, and NRSV all translate "appointed." BDAG notes "the relation of Jesus to God" (p. 839). An analogous usage in English would be the use of the verb "made" for English naval officers when they were appointed a post captain (see Patrick O'Brian's Aubrey-Maturin novels).\f* as also Moses [was faithful] in his whole\f + NET reads without ὅλῳ. In a note, the editors explain that it was added "apparently in anticipation of Heb 3:5 which quotes directly from Num 12:7. On balance, the omission better explains the rise of ὅλῳ (holō, “all”) than vice versa."\f* house.
\v 3 For this one was worthy of greater glory than Moses, as much as the one who built a house has greater honor than the house.
\v 4 For every house is built by someone, but the builder of all things is God.\f + This is a not-so-subtle argument that Jesus himself is God because he, Jesus, is the builder of this "house." And God is the builder of all things.\f*
\v 5 And Moses on the one hand was faithful in his whole house as a servant to be a testimony for what was spoken,
\v 6 but Christ as a son in his house. Which\f + I am not satisfied with this translation, but I am not sure what the syntactical function of the relative pronoun οὗ is here. \f* we are [that] house, if we adhere firmly to the confidence and boasting of hope.
\p
